e time to check your advertising and listings.\nPlease make sure they are shown correctly.\nNow is the time, also, to arrange for additional\nlistings in the new directory to show the names of\nother members of your family or business firm. Addi\ntional listings are almost a necessity if someone at\nyour house has a family name different from yours.\nIf you are in business, it will pay you to advertise\nin the Yellow Pages. That's where nine out of ten\npeople look the moment they want to buy your\nproducts and services. And you'll be wise, too, to\norder a Bold Type Listing in the Alphabetical Section.\nThe Diamond State Telephone\nCompany\nf\n2 Vi\nff\nik fj]\n\nI oj\nC\nVI)\ni\\\n\u00e0\nrv\n\n0\n\n<7\nmm\nA\nc\nv\n\nfU\n\nnS 1\nA\ni\nI,\n0\nI\nj]\ns:\nDll\nv'v\n\\KS \u00e9\n\nvX;\n\nattsawwj\n\nN,\nGeorge J. Hogendobler and Mar\ntha E., and Lester P. Adams and\nArlene, to Raymond H. Elliott and\nLouise G., Laurel, Lot.\nLemuel J. Holt to Thomas L.\nWinterbottom and Edith D., Bal\ntimore Hd., 7 acres and 14 perch\nes, 2% acres.\nWilliam A. Joseph and V. Louise\nto Kover M. Hudson, Sr. and Flor\nence G., Lewes and Reho. Hd.,\nLots 11, 12, 13, and 14, Sec. B.\nFulton J. Downing and Anna H.,\nto Franklin V. Vleck and Ruth A.,\nReho. Hd., Lots 17 and 18 and\nof Lot 16, Blk. 24.\nBeaver Dam Realty, Inc., to\nThomas R. Soukup, Jr., and June\nC., Seaford Hd., Lot 58.\nFrances A. Staplefor^ to Charles\nJ. Rlbsam and Ethel M., Lewes\nand Reho. Hd., Lot 16.\nJames E. Hearn and Ida K., to\nPreston E. Evans and Hazel M.,\nCedar Creek Hd., 18 acres.\nDaniel J. Layton and Laura H.,\nto Mabel A. Green, Lewes and\nReho. Hd., Lots 5 and 6, Blk. B.\nSussex Shores Realty Co., to\nRichard S. Luckett, Jr., and Vir\nginia S., Baltimore Hd., Lot 7,\nBlk. 2.\nFred T. Carey and Mary A., to\nFred Lloyd Bullock and Mary J.,\nBaltimore Hd., acre.\nWilliam B. Walsh to Carl G.\nPrettyman and Verna M., Lewes,\n1% acres and Lot.\nHarry C. Eashum and Mamie F.,\nto John W. Barnes and Mary S.,\nBethany Beach, Lot 22, Blk. 9.\nLewes Trust Co. to A. Dalton\nMyers, Lewes and Reho Hd., Lots\n37 and 38.\nWilliam B. Venable, Jr., to Ver\nnon C. Wingate and Alma G., Lit\ntle Creek Hd., 1.2 acres.\nHarold L. Griffin and Lillian E.,\nto Robert L. Whaley and Patricia\nO., Laurel, Lot 26 and 27, of Lot\n28. Sec. B.\nGregory J. Aires and Sallie Belle,\nto Sarah Elizabeth Chase Lee,\nLewes and Reho. Hd., Lot 13, Blk.\nD:\nWilliam Johnson and Lucille, to\nRobert L. Cannon, Indian River\nHd., 2 15/00 acres.\nDelbert D. Moore and Idetta L.,\nto George R. Kendrick and Esther\nE., Indian River Hd., Lot.\nDelshore Co., Inc., to Edmund\nC. Pusey and Gertrude H., Balti\nmore Hd., Lots 17, 18, 19, 20 and\n21 and an unnumbered lot.\nSea Gull Realty Corp., to Ed\nmund C. Pusey and Gertrude H.,\nBaltimore Hd., Lots 22, 23, 24, 25,\n26 and 27.\nLizzie C. Easham and Orrie to\nRaymond J. Lynch and/or Kathe\nrine V., Baltimore Hd., 10887 sq. ft.\nEmory T. Sirman and Pauline\nto Vinol L. Lynch and Flossie S.,\nBroad Creek Hd., Lot 2, (10 acres).\nEmory T. Sirman and Pauline\nto Arnette Sirman and Pauline\nSirman, Broad Creek Hd., 1 acre.\nJohn G. Walter and Dorothy E.,\nto Rockford E. Murray and Alberta\nM., Baltimore Hd., no dimension\ngiven.\nHoward F. Lane and Flossie to\nLucian T. Jones and Ruth C., Broad\nCreek Hd., 8% acres.\nHoward F. Lane and Flossie to\nLouise H. Callaway and Elsie,\nBroad Creek Hd., 7.47 acres.\nElwood A. Layton and Cubulee\nL., to John L. Wilkins and Hattie\nLouise, Georgetown Hd., 9,000 sq.\nJob Staten Culver and Beulah\nMay to Robert W. Hupp and Mar\ntha M., Little Creek Hd., 300 x 75\nLucy S. Powers to James A.\nCampbell and Louise J., Reho.,\nUnit #31 and 32.\nCorbett E. Daisey and Elsie to\nRawlins H. Peed and Itcne, Lewes,\nLot 3, Blk. W.\nLee Hawkini to Otto W. Huff\nman and Pea.'lie A., Broad Creek\nHd., .39 acre.\nDavid Richard Brittingham and\nViriginia A., to Mieczyslaw Zola\nand Ruth Ella, Lewes and Reho.\nHd., Lot.\nLewes Trust Co., to James M.\nTunnell, Jr., and Robert W\u201e Lew\nes and Reho. Hd., Lot 2 and E.\nof Lot 3.\nJoseph F. Draper and Ethel H\u201e\nto Grover C. Draper, Cedar Creek\nHd., 15% acres.\nGrover C. Draper and Ella S.,\nto Douglas C. Hudson and Frances\nOlivia, Cedar Creek Hd., 12%\nacres.\nSussex Shores Realty Co., to\nStanley W. Krakowiak and Sabina\nA., Baltimore Hd., Lot 56.\nLester C. Newton and Pearl I.,\nto Del. Electric Cooperative, Inc.,\nNorthwest Fork Hd., 2 acres.\nNettie B. Hitchens to Leonard\nRaymond Hitchens and Emma\nLouise, Little Creek Hd., 4% acres.\nFrances G. Custis and Edwin S.,\nto James C. Cuyler and Marjorie\nA., LeWes, Part of Lots 8 and 10,\nBlk. II.\nEdith W. Hancock to Tasker Da\nvidson and/or Irene, Baltimore\nHd., 2% acres.\nElmer F. Quillen and Lottie;\nHerschel H. Quillen and Pearl to\nRobert A. Norman and Nellie\nBaltimore Hd., Lots 27 and 36.\nLizzie M. Bennett to Sara E.\nSharp, Cedar Creek Hd., 67 acres,\nand 103 sq. perches.\nHarper Feed Mills, Inc., to Hir\nam N. Lasher and Bertha; Albert\nS. Cosgrove and Margaret, Indian\nRiver Hd., 10.79 acres.\nWilliam Hudson Derrickson and\nPatricia Adkins to Henry L. Dorz\nback and Noel K., Seaford Hd., Lot\nft.\nft\nLi.\nDonato DeBlasio to Louis P.\nlanire and Delores, Lewes and\nReho. Hd., 4971 sq. ft.\nMiildred Parker Brain to Mary\nK. Kinder, Lewes and Reho. Hd.,\nLots 159 and 161.\nNO DEW AFTER DROUGHT\nHUNTINGTON, W. Va. (JP\nThe drought in West Virginia this\nsummer -cut the supplies of two\nkinds of dew\u2014plain water and the\nmountain kind with the mule kick\nalso known as moonshine.\nDavid H. Walker, a government\ninvestigator, explains that moun\ntain streams which supply water for\nstills have dried up, cutting moon\nshining to a trickle. The 'shiners\nare too shiftless to tote water up\nthe hills from dug wells, he says.\nWeekly Tree Talk\nIDENTIFY TREES BY COLOR\nOF THEIR AUTUMN LEAVES\nAutumn colors will be brilliant\nin some areas of the east this fall\nless spectacular in others. Where\ndrought has robbed trees of mois\nture, the color display wijl lack the\nusual brilliance.'\nHalf the fun in motoring to or\nstrolling* in October woodlands is\nidentifying tre'es with outstanding\ncolor roles. Roland K. Dobson,\nrepresentative of the Bartlett Tree\nExpert Company, suggest the fol\nlowing chart to use on a foliage\ntour: 4\nEarly Uolorlng\nRed Maple\u2014Crimson to winy red\nDogwood\u2014vivid red\nBirch\u2014butter yellow\nSugar Maple\u2014flaming reds, or\nanges, and yellows\nWhite Ash\u2014 purpl\u00e9\nElm\u2014pale yellow\n31 hl-Auf uni u\nGinkgo\u2014brilliant yeLow\nYellow wood\u2014sunset gold\nTulip Tree\u2014rich gold\nSweetgum\u2014shouting crimson\nRedbud\u2014mellow yellow\nMountain Ash\u2014purple\nLate Autumn\nScarlet Oak\u2014bright scarlet\nBlack Gum\u2014deep burgundy\nPin Oak\u2014rusty red\nRed Oak\u2014dark red to russet\nHickory\u2014leathery yellow to\nbrown\nNorway Maple\u2014buttercup yellow\nContrary to popular belief, it is\nnot Jack Frost behind the autum\nnal display. \"Hidden\" pigments of\nyellow and red come to the fore as\nchlorphyll green breaks down.\nSunny days and cool nights\u2014\nwith ample moisture in leaves\u2014\ncause gorgeous colors in fall.\nNo two trees are exactly alike.\nAncestral characteristics make one\nmore brilliant than another. If\nyou're a camer.a fan, go back to\nthe same brilliant tree autumn af\nter autumn; its autumn colors will\nremain true year after year. That\nis why, if you want to plant a young\ntree for color, select it in the fall\nwhen the leaves are turning.\n-S>\nDECEPTIVE WOMAN\nKNOXVILLE, Tenu. (\u00c6*)\nsooner had a frantic mother tele\nphoned city police reporting the\ndisappearance of her little girl than\nthe police had a new problem on\ntheir hands: To find the parents of\na boy found wandering alone on\nKnoxville streets.\nAfter trying to entertain the boy\nfor about three hours, the officers\nreceived another phone call from\nthe mother of the lost girl.\n\"I forgot to tell you,\" said the\nwoman, \"that Peggy might be mis\ntaken for a boy\",\nDoing a double take, officers de\ncided that Peggy, indeed, might.\nThe jeans-clad, crew-cut found\n\"boy\" turned out to be the \"lost\ngirl.\nNo\nAIR CONDITIONING-TEMPERATURES MADE TO ORDER-A\" NEW LOW COST. GET A DEMONSTRATIONi\nMORE PEOPLE DRiVE CHEVROLETS THAN ANY OTHER CAR\nCOAST-TO-COAST\n1\nECONOMY RUN PROVES IT\nf\nCHEVY COSTS\nLESS 10 DRIVE\nTest run from Los Angeles to New\nYork by the three leading low-priced\ncars showed Chevrolet costs less to\noperate, with up to 17% greater fuel\neconomy!\nr\nI\n4\n\n\n\nWhen fuel and operating costs for cars are\nofficially checked for 2,873 miles, from\nLos Angeles to New York, what happens?\nIn the certified findings of the NATA*,\nChevrolet delivered up to 17% greater fuel\neconomy, and lower total cost for the trip\u2014\nproof that Chevrolet costs least to operate\nof the three leading low-priced cars that\nwere tested!\nThis economy record only confirms\nChevy's reputation for money-saving ways.\nYou expect Chevrolet engines to wring extra\nmiles out of a gallon of gas\u2014just as yoii\nexpect finer craftsmanship in the way a\nChevrolet is built. Why wait to put new\nsparkle\u2014and economy\u2014in the miles you\ndrive? See your Chevrolet dealer soon!\n*National Automotive Testing Association\n&55\ni\nW:\na\nfv.;\nm\nII\nt\nV-';\n\n\nV\nx-.\nW&:\nw\nj 'M\nm\n\u25a0y\nW\n\nftoj pfea si\n\nx',:,\n\nm\ny// y\nX\u00ff;\nW\u00fb\nGET A WINNING DEAL ON A NEW CHEVY\n\u2014THE GETTING'S EXTRA GOOD!\nOnlv franchised Chevrolet dealers display this\nfamous trademark\nSee Your Local Authorized\nChevrolet Dealer\nChevy finishes 2,873-mile test with Jp to 17% greater fuel economy\nHOUSTON\nMrs. Viola Thistlcwood\nPhon\u00ab: Milford 4944\nChurch\n29th:\nnews for Sunday, Sept.\nSunday School at 10 a. m., with\nRobert H. Yerkes, Sr., General\nSupt. Alvin Brown, Junior Sup't;\nMrs. Charles Pearson, Cradle Roll\nSupt. As vacation time is over, the\nchildren and young folks have re\nturned to school, let's see if we can\nincrease the number qf our church\nschool on Sunday. There' is room\nfor all and teachers and classes for\neach and everyone.\nAt 11 a. m\u201e the service of wor\nship begins with the organ prelude\nwith Mrs. Agnes Webb at the c\u00f4h\nscle. May we enter the Sanctuary\nwith the Spirit of worship and\npeel to give and receive a blessing.\nCall to worship by the minister,\nRev. Ray KirWan who will deliver\nthe sermon.\nAt the Loyalty Service Sunday\nmorning, both the Chancel Choir\nwith Mrs. Robert Yerkes and Miss\nLois Slaughter, as Directors, and\n*he- Junior Choir with Mrs. Hazel\nLemmon, as Director and Miss Con\nnie Parvis, as pianist, will render\nspecial selections. Let's all make\na special effort to attend this ser\nvice and bring as many with us as\npossible for a Christian first con\ncern is for others.\nThe Methodist Men, the Metho\ndist Youth Felowship and the\nYoung Adult Fellowship are all\nplanning to resume activities in the\nhear future. Announcements of\ntheir meeting date will be forth\nThem were 10 from Houston\nMethodist Church present at the\nGroup Quarterly Conference, in\nMilford, Tuesday, September 17,\nwhich was most gratifying.*\nRally Day will be observed in\nthe Sunday School Sunday, October\n6, from 10 to 11 a. m. This would be\na good time to get the attendance\nback on the right track, after thh\nsummer period. A special Rally\nex\n\u00e0oming soon.\nWhy \"Good-Time\nCharlie'' Suffers\nUneasy Bladder\nSuch a common thing as unwise eating\nor drinking may be a source of mild, but\nannoying bladder irritations\u2014making you\nfeel restless, tense, and uncomfortable. And\nif restless nights, with nagging backache,\nheadache or muscular aches and pains due\nto over-exertion, strain or emotional upset,\nare adding to your misery \u2014don't wait\ntry Doan's Pills.\nDoan's Pills have'three outstanding ad\nvanta^s\u2014act in three ways for your speedy\nreturn to comfort. 1\u2014They have an easing\nsoothing effect on bladder irritations. 2\u2014A\nfast pain-relieving action on nagging back\nache, headaches, muscular aches and pains.\n3\u2014A wonderfully mild diuretic action thru\nthe kidneys, tending to increase the output\nof the 15 miles of kidney tubes. So, get the\nsame happy relief millions h.we enjoyed for\nover 60 years. Ask for new, 'arge, economy\nsize and save money. Get Doan's Pills today t\nDay Program will be nresented on\nSunday evening at 8 u clock, spon\nsored by the Sunday School, to\nwhich every one is cordially in\nvited.\nMrs. Jennie Hendricks, who has\nbeen seriously ill in Milford Mem\norial Hospital, the past week, was\nable to return to her home on Mon\nday morning. She is still quite Ill,\nbut is improving some. Mrs. Min\nnie Chism is taking care of her.\nWe were very sorry when we\nlearned of the misfortune that be\nfell Mrs. Charles Trice, of Milford,\nwhen she fell and injured her back\nmost severely. She' is in Milford\nMemorial Hospital and we surely\ntrust her recovery will be speedy.\nAt one time in goneby years, the\nTrices lived across the street from\nthe writer of these items and they\nwere wonderful neighbors.\nMr. Basait Rayne, of Wadsworth,\nOhio, spent Friday evening with\nhis cousins, Mr. and Mrs. James\nSmack and Mrs. Annie Smack.\nMr. and Mrs. Oley F. Sapp and\nMrs. Vaughn Warren attended the\nSouthern States Stock holders ban\nquet on Thursday evening. In Mil\nford.\nMrs. G. A. Morgan and Mrs.\nJames Clendaniel, of Dover, spen* j\nSaturday with Mr. and Mrs. Fey!\nNewman, of Milford.\nMrs. C. Walter Wharton and Mrs.\nRuth Sapp spent Wednesday after\nnoon visiting with Mr. and Mrs.\nArthur Taylor.\nMr. and Mrs. Charles Koeneman\nwere Sunday dinner guests of Mr. I\nand Mrs. William Malcolm, at\nBoothwyn, Pa. It was a surprise for j\nMrs. Koeneman whose birthday an\nniversary fell on September 28th.\nOther relatives and friends were\ninvited and wished many happy\nWANTED\n\nj\nCORN\nCALL US BEFORE YOU SELL\nNEWTON'S\nBridgcville, Del.\nPhone 2.\u00cf.TI\n9-13-3\u00bb\nreturns of the day for Mrs. Koene\nman.\nRaymond Marvel and Richard\nSimpson went to Richmond, Va.,\non Monday to represent Delaware\nin a rural expedition show. They\nwill also be judges at a dairy con\ntest.\nMr. and Mrs. Glenn Green are be\ning congratulated upon the birth\nof a fine 9-lb. 8oz. girl born in Mil\nford Memorial Hospital last week\nand both mother and daughter are\nfine and Dad\u2014well he will make\nthe grade it is hoped.\nAmong those who attended the\nDelaware Sheep and Wool Raisers\nAssociation dinner held at the\nHotel Milford. Tuesday evening,\nwere, Mr. and Mrs. Calvin V. Hollis,\nJr. and children, Calvin the 3rd and\nMary Carol, Mr. and Mrs. Floyd\nBlessing, Mr. and Mrs. Earl Ram\nbo, Sr. and son, Charles, and Mr. II\nRobert H. Yerkes, Sr.\nJust a thought, \"That which I\nkeep I lose. That which I sire\naway I keep.\"\nLongest river in China is the\nYangtze, 3,100 miles.\nn\nA MEAL WITHOUT MEAT IS A\nMEAL INCOMPLETE\nu\nWhite Packing Company, Inc., will fill your freezer with\nbeef, veal, lamb, pork, fowl and vegetables.\nWe sell Freezer Plans or Wholesale Cuts of your choice of meats. Yog can\npurchase meats wrapped and frozen or fresh and you do the wrapping.\nIf you so desire, we will finance. Come in and see us soon.\nTurn at Thomas Best Store in Nassau\nWHITE PACKING COMPANY, INC.\nPhenes 5331-9921\nNew Road\u2014Lewes, Del.\n2-22-tf\nTFDDY BEAR MAX\nn\u00ab CDAKIIf I flORI C\nUK. mAIMR L. feUblX\nCluropractie Physician\nFriday: 7:30 to\nPHONE DOVER 2284\n104 8. Bradford St., Dover, Delaware\n\u00ab-ll-tf\nWAPAKONETA, Ohio (/P)\u2014 TL\nA. McLean, known in these parts\nas Ohio's \"Teddy Bear Man\", has\ndistributed more than 10,000 teddy\nbears to hospitalized children.\nSince the early part of 1952, Mc\nLean has helped make boys and\ngirls \u00e0 little happier while they are\nconvalescing in hospitals.\nMcLean himself was hospitalized\nfor some time as a boy.\nHundreds of persons in north\nwestern Ohio contribute to the pro\nject and MacLean also obtains\nfunds through the redemption of\nsales tax stamps.\nRead The Classified Ads","height":"25182","width":"20091"}}
